@military
title: Something?

The Left, led by Paul Levi, have used the conference to bring forward a proposal that the SPD categorically reject the Reichswehr, call for its abolition, and advocate replacing it with workers’ militias under direct proletarian control. They argue that any cooperation with the existing army would only serve to legitimise an instrument of bourgeois repression and betray the interests of the working class. However, if we were to accept such an agreement, it would almost certainly alienate moderate and liberal partners in any prospective coalition, making stable government virtually impossible.
The Reformists and Centrist elements, led by Carl Severing, are firmly against the Left’s abolitionist motion. In a time of crisis, they maintain, the party must retain a professional military force, albeit one fully subordinated to strict parliamentary and civilian oversight, to safeguard democratic institutions. Severing’s amendment proposes a modified draft defence programme that “republicanises” the officer corps rather than dismantling it, balancing the need for robust national defence with the SPD’s commitment to democracy. Severing’s address emphasized that only by acknowledging the positive aspects of the Reichswehr could it be truly republicanized, framing his amendment as the blueprint for a democratic defense policy.






